Data description

## [1] "961 out of 133940 cars are individualized."

Checking horizontal vs. vertical customizations

The following multilevel models are included in the below table. All are linear mixed effects models containing random effects of Car Type, Body Type, Color, Fuel Type, and Transmission Type on the intercept.

  • Model1: Normal ML-regression including all variables.
  • Model2: Model1 + Interaction of individual package and seller type.
  • Model3: Model1 + Interaction of individual package and age in days.
  • Model4: Like model 1, but the DV is the system-assigned price category (1-cheap to 7-expensive).
  • Model5: Model4 + Interaction of individual package and seller type.

## NOTE: privatesellerindividual is not a high-order term in the model

Calculating relative popularity (inverted relative uniqueness)

\[ Popularity_{i} = \prod_{feature = 1}^{n_{feature}} f(\frac{Count_{feature}}{n_{observations}}) \]

\[ Relative Popularity_{i} = (\frac{Popularity_{i}}{max(Popularity_{i},...,Popularity_{n})})*100 \]

Where:

  • Features are the aspects of the observations described below.
  • \(Count_{feature}\) is the count of all observations that are equal to this feature for \(Observation_{i}\)

Uniqueness is calculated in 3 different ways:

  • Popularity1: Multiplied frequency ratio of Car Model, Fuel Type, Color, Body Type, and Transmission Type
  • Popularity2: Features all car features of Popularity1, but adds the features Power (in HP),HUD, Laser,Sport, “Glasdach”, ACC, “Standheizung”,LED-Light, Leather Interior, Individual-Package, and Navigation System.
  • Popularity3: Features all car features of Popularity1, but adds the feature Power (in HP).

This was done in order to try to calculate “uniqueness” rather than “feature-richness”. While Popularity1 errs on the side of “popularity vs. uniqueness” of the configuration, Popularity2 errs on the side of “feature-rich vs. bare-boned” configuration and Uniqueness3 tries to take a middle-ground.

Again, all are all are linear mixed effects models containing random effects of Car Type, Body Type, Color, Fuel Type, and Transmission Type on the intercept. The regression including Popularity3 was unsuccessful.

In order to avoid multicollinearity, several other features have been removed.

Holding duration

For these regressions, the data set was restricted to cars that only have had 1 previous owner. This means that the previous (first) owner configurated the car and now is selling it. This is to check whether the configuration has an impact on holding duration.

Again, all are all are linear mixed effects models containing random effects of Car Type, Body Type, Color, Fuel Type, and Transmission Type on the intercept.
